"Button K., Rothengatter W.","Motor transport, greenhouse gases and economic instruments",1997,"International Journal of Environment and Pollution","7","3",,"327","342",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0030714244&partnerID=40&md5=500cd79b3f6983a9b3e655ec3b62e61c","Institute of Public Policy, George Mason University, Fairfax, VA 22030, United States; Inst. F. Wirtschaftpolitik/W., Universität Karlsruhe, Karlsruhe, Germany","Button, K., Institute of Public Policy, George Mason University, Fairfax, VA 22030, United States; Rothengatter, W., Inst. F. Wirtschaftpolitik/W., Universität Karlsruhe, Karlsruhe, Germany","Motorized transport is the generator of several forms of negative externality including the uncompensated emissions of greenhouse (global warming) gases. This paper looks at some of the underlying economic issues pertaining to policy-making designed to limit the extent of these externalities. It sets out the basic nature of the problem and outlines our knowledge of the link between the physical sciences involved and the relevant economic theory. It focuses, in particular, on the strict question of quasi-internalization in the context of a global externality.","Economic instruments; Global warming; Motor transport","Economic and social effects; Global warming; Greenhouse effect; Public policy; Economic instruments; Motor transportation",,,,,,"(1994) Energy Use and Emissions from Passenger Transport in London. Report to London Transport, , AEA Technology, London; Acutt, M.Z., Modelling greenhouse gas emissions from cars in Great Britain (1995) Transportation Planning and Technology, , forthcoming; Alfsen, K., Glomsrød, S., Secondary benefits of climate policies: Some tentative calculations (1992) Internal Note, , Central Bureau of Statistics, Oslo; Barrett, S., Economic instruments for climate change policy (1991) Responding to Climate Change, , Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development, OECD, Paris; Baumol, W., Oates, W., The 